  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "If we evolved from apes then why are there still apes around today?",
  "response": "The idea that humans evolved from apes can be a bit misleading. A more accurate way to understand it is that humans and modern apes share a common ancestor. This ancestor lived many millions of years ago and over time, different branches of its descendants evolved into different species, including the various species of apes we see today and, eventually, humans.\n\nHere's a step-by-step breakdown:\n\n1. **Common Ancestor**: About 7 to 8 million years ago, there was a common ancestor to both humans and modern apes.\n\n2. **Divergent Evolution**: Over time, different groups of this ancestor's descendants evolved in different ways due to various factors like geographic separation, environmental changes, and genetic mutations. This process led to the development of distinct lineages.\n\n3. **Hominin Lineage**: One lineage eventually led to the hominins, which includes early human ancestors like Australopithecus and, eventually, the genus Homo, to which modern humans (Homo sapiens) belong.\n\n4. **Ape Lineages**: Other lineages evolved into the various species of apes we see today, such as chimpanzees, gorillas, and orangutans.\n\nSo, the reason there are still apes around today is that they continued to evolve along their own paths, separate from the path that led to humans. Just as different branches of a family tree can lead to different relatives, different evolutionary branches from a common ancestor can lead to different species.\n\nIn summary, humans did not evolve from modern apes; rather, humans and modern apes share a common ancestor from which they diverged millions of years ago.",
